  "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EHeadless CMS architectures are often pitched as a universal upgrade: decouple the front end, unlock any framework, deliver content anywhere. For the right team, that pitch holds. For many others, the tradeoffs show up months after launch, long after the slide deck has been archived.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EWhat you actually gain\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe real wins are flexibility and reuse. A single content model can feed a marketing site, a mobile app, a kiosk, and a partner integration without duplicating editorial effort. Front-end teams can choose the stack that fits the channel \u2014 Next.js for the web, a native app for mobile, something lean for email \u2014 without asking the CMS for permission.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EWhat you give up\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EPreview becomes harder. Routing becomes your problem. The \u201Cedit in place\u201D experience editors take for granted in a coupled CMS often needs to be rebuilt. And every capability the CMS used to handle \u2014 redirects, forms, search, personalisation \u2014 becomes a decision you have to make and a service you have to run.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EWho benefits most\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETeams with multiple channels, strong front-end capability, and a clear content strategy tend to thrive headless. Teams with a single website, a small engineering team, and editors who value the all-in-one experience are often better served by a traditional setup. Neither choice is a failure of imagination; they are different answers to different problems.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EThe question worth asking\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBefore committing to headless, ask what problem it is solving that your current stack cannot. If the answer is \u201Cnone, but it feels modern,\u201D keep looking. The best architecture is the one your team can operate a year from now without resenting it.\u003C/p\u003E"
}]]></Value>
    </bodyText>
